\strong{Additional Information}
Cardiac arrests occur when the heart suddenly stops functioning, hence impairing blood flow to the brain, organs and tissues. When this occurs, the person becomes unresponsive and may occasionally have a few slight twitches. Normal pulse and breathing stop momentarily. Cardiac arrest is usually associated with diseases that affect the heart's capacity to operate or coronary artery malfunction. These illnesses cause cardiac arrest more frequently than other disorders. There are many causes of sudden cardiac death. They include blood clots (the most common cause), an abnormal heart rhythm, a heart attack, abnormal heartbeat (usually a very fast one), high blood pressure, low blood pressure, rupture of the main artery, heart failure and extreme physical activity.

Frequently, cardiac arrests happen without prior warnings, however, some patients may experience symptoms  before having a cardiac arrest. Symptoms that suggest cardiac arrest include any of the following; sudden collapse, no normal breathing, nor a pulse, the person is unresponsive to pinching and cannot speak and there is a near-terminal loss of consciousness. Note that a cardiac arrest is not the same as a heart attack.

Cardiac arrests should be treated as quickly as possible. The earlier the intervention, the better. Most hospitals have chest pain or cardiac arrests teams consisting of doctors, nurses and other experts who are trained to care for these patients with the utmost speed and efficiency. To get help immediately, call 911, your local emergency number, or ask someone to drive you to a hospital emergency room. A healthcare provider can evaluate you further and decide on appropriate steps. Never, ever, disregard the possibility of a cardiac arrest.

If you think you could be suffering cardiac issues, please see your doctor immediately. Remember - a cardiac arrest is different from a heart attack - though these two could sometimes occur together. Never, ever, disregard the possibility of a cardiac arrest.

Hello! I am sorry to hear that you are experiencing back pains and stiffness, as well as aching joints. From the information provided, there are several possible explanations for your symptoms. 

However, before I offer any potential causes, can you clarify how long you have experienced this discomfort? In addition, have you sustained any injuries or engaged in strenuous activities that may have triggered or aggravated your symptoms? Also, have you noticed any other symptoms like numbness, weakness, or tingling sensations in your arms or legs? Knowing these specifics will assist us in further narrowing down the possibilities and better comprehending your condition.

Some likely reasons for your complaints include but are not limited to: 
* Muscle strain or sprains; 
* Inflamed muscles (myofasciitis) or ligaments; 
* Herniated disc or spinal stenosis, which can cause pressure on nerves; 
* Degenerative conditions such as osteoarthritis, spondylosis, or facet joint dysfunction; 
* Poor posture, body mechanics, or muscle imbalances; 
* Chronic conditions such as rheumatoid arthritis, fibromyalgia, or polymyalgia rheumatica.

It is crucial to note that pinpointing the root cause of back pain and related symptoms can prove challenging, requiring careful consideration of numerous factors. To achieve accurate diagnoses and effective treatment strategies, healthcare experts must analyze patients' complaints, clinical examination findings, and relevant diagnostic tests (e.g., X-rays, MRI scans).

Therefore, I strongly advise seeking consultation with a healthcare professional, such as a physician, physical medicine specialist, or orthopedic specialist, who can conduct an extensive evaluation, consider your unique circumstances and medical history, and render an accurate diagnosis. They will also develop a personalized treatment plan encompassing medication, therapy, lifestyle modifications, or other appropriate interventions to alleviate your symptoms.
